1. The Prediction Problem ¶

In this project I'll be exploring a dataset of Vancouver Airbnb listings from 2023. Specifically, I will create a customer satisfaction regression model to try to predict a listing's review_scores_rating, as a proxy for the popularity of the listing. Airbnb could use this sort of model to recommend new listings with high potential for customer satisfaction to site browsers. Furthermore, this model could identify the factors which are most important in predicting high ratings, which hosts can then use to improve their own listings.

The documentation of the dataset can be found here.

Upon initial review of the dataset, it seems like a few of the features were extracted from name, but this extraction was incomplete. For example, there is a column for beds that matches the information from the name column, yet bedrooms is empty, despite the data also being available in the name column. Let's start by extracting the rest of the missing information so I can reduce the data size from dropping the redundant name column. Additionally, I will convert (and rename) bathrooms_text to be a numeric feature instead.

I also noticed that price is formatted as a string starting with $, and host_acceptance_rate and host_response_rate are formatted as strings ending with %. I will remove these as well and convert them to numeric types to make analysis a bit easier.

In [4]:
import re

def extract_bedroom_number(string):
    """
    Assuming the word 'bedroom' exists anywhere in the string, extract the number
    before it; otherwise return nothing
    
    The regular expression pattern:
    \d+ matches one or more digits
    (?:\.\d+)? optionally matches a decimal point followed by one or more digits
    \s*bedroom matches zero or more whitespace characters followed by 'bedroom'
    """
    match = re.search(r'(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s*bedroom', string)
    if match:
        return float(match.group(1))
    else:
        return None

def extract_bathroom_number(string):
    """
    Extract the leading character from the bathroom_text string and return this 
    remaining number of bathrooms as a float, or None if missing value
    """
    if pd.isna(string):    
        return None
            
    match = re.match(r'\d+\.\d+|\d+', string)
    if match:
        return float(match.group())
    return None

def convert_price(price):
    """
    Remove the $ from a given price and return the remaining number as a float
    """
    if pd.notna(price):
        if isinstance(price, str):
            if price.startswith('$'):
                price = price[1:]  
            # Remove any commas (for cases like $1,000)
            price = price.replace(',', '')
            return float(price)
    return price

def convert_percents(string):
    """
    Remove the % from the end of a string and return the remaining number as a float
    """
    if pd.notna(string):
        if isinstance(string, str):
            string = string.replace(',', '')
            return float(string[:-1])
    return string

The numeric features in this dataset vary quite a bit and are reported in different measurements (%, $, #). I will scale most of them using a StandardScaler.

However, 2 particular numeric features stand out to me that may be better suited to a different method. Even though we have a feature for neighbourhood groups, latitude and longitude may be useful in revealing additional patterns about how location affects the reviews a listing receives and thus popularity. For example, maybe 2 neighbourhoods that are geographically closer north get more reviews than southern listings, or maybe there's a cluster of area that's popular but not encapsulated by the neighbourhood groups. By binning these features into a range of values instead of using their floating point representation, perhaps we can obtain more informative insights.

def remove_html_tags(text):
    """
    Remove HTML tags from a string
    """
    clean = re.compile('<.*?>')
    return re.sub(clean, '', text)

4. Feature engineering ¶

In the dataset, there are a few time series features that I don't think on their own will be too informative on the prediction problem. My goal is to identify general patterns that popular listings have in common; the exact date that a first review was posted or when a host created their account shouldn't have any direct impact on popularity and would just add complexity to the model.

Instead, these time series features can be used to create more informative/relevant features. One example that may be insightful to engineer is days_to_first_review, which subtracts the date that the listing received its first review (first_review) from the date the listing was created to calculate how long it took a listing to get its first review. Since we don't have the exact date that the listing was created, I will use the date that the host created their profile (host_since) as a close substitute. This new feature could potentially indicate market demand, i.e. if a particular neighbourhood tends to receive reviews faster, it's likely to be a more popular tourist location. Similarly, a short turnaround time to a first review can also reveal patterns in the hosts' listings, potentially suggesting effective strategies.

In [15]:
# Add new feature to train data
X_train['host_since'] = pd.to_datetime(X_train['host_since'])
X_train['first_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_train['first_review'])     
X_train['days_to_first_review'] = (X_train['first_review'] - X_train['host_since']).dt.days

# Add new feature to test data
X_test['host_since'] = pd.to_datetime(X_test['host_since'])
X_test['first_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_test['first_review'])     
X_test['days_to_first_review'] = (X_test['first_review'] - X_test['host_since']).dt.days

The dataset I'm using was last updated on December 13, 2023. In contrast to the feature created above, I will also add a new feature last_given_review, which subtracts the date that the last review was given (last_review) from the date the dataset was last updated, to calculate in relative terms how many days ago the last review was posted. While the most recent review may not necessarily have been positive, this additional feature shows engagement (we can hypothesize that listings with a shorter gap since their most recent review are more popular).

In [16]:
last_update_date = pd.Timestamp('2023-12-13')

# Add new feature to train data
X_train['last_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_train['last_review'])
X_train['days_since_last_review'] = (last_update_date - X_train['last_review']).dt.days
        
# Add new feature to test data
X_test['last_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_test['last_review'])
X_test['days_since_last_review'] = (last_update_date - X_test['last_review']).dt.days

Another feature that can be engineered from the temporal data is review_frequency, calculated by subtracting first_review from last_review, then dividing that amount by total number_of_reviews. In other words, this feature measures the average duration (in days) between a listing's reviews. If a listing has a higher review_frequency, this may indicate higher popularity.

In [17]:
# Add new feature to train data
X_train['first_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_train['first_review'])
X_train['last_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_train['last_review'])
        
# Compute the review frequency
X_train['review_frequency'] = (X_train['last_review'] - X_train['first_review']).dt.days / X_train['number_of_reviews']

# Replace infinite and NaN results when number of reviews is zero.
X_train['review_frequency'].replace([pd.NA, float('inf'), -float('inf')], None, inplace=True)

# Add new feature to test data
X_test['first_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_test['first_review'])
X_test['last_review'] = pd.to_datetime(X_test['last_review'])
X_test['review_frequency'] = (X_test['last_review'] - X_test['first_review']).dt.days / X_test['number_of_reviews']
X_test['review_frequency'].replace([pd.NA, float('inf'), -float('inf')], None, inplace=True)

Step 2: Convert Relevant Data Types¶

This dataset has a special feature: host_id. Although it is represented numerically, it should actually be treated as a categorical feature because it serves as a unique identifier for hosts, who may have multiple listings. I will convert this feature to be of type string to fit in with the other categorical features that will be one-hot encoded. With this feature, we can explore and compare listings between top hosts and potentially draw patterns there.

In [19]:
X_train['host_id'] = X_train['host_id'].astype(str)

As mentioned in the EDA section, there are many numeric features, all with different ranges. Below are the features I've chosen to keep. Some numeric features (host_response_rate, host_acceptance_rate, bedrooms, beds, baths) have a small amount of missing values. Since the rest of the rows could still contain informative data, I am choosing to indicate missing values as -1.

Step 4: Encode Binary, Ordinal, and then regular Categorical Features¶

Of the categorical features, I noticed a few features that can be represented differently. By identifying features with binary or ordinal values, the model's computational efficiency can be improved. Only one categorical feature contains missing values: host_response_time. Since there are a few hundred missing values in this feature and the original dataset is not that big, I want to avoid deleting rows. Instead, I will convert NaNs to a string "Unknown", since again, the rest of the rows should still be highly informative.

Step 5: Handle Text Data¶

This dataset contains 2 raw text features: neighborhood_overview and host_about. neighborhood_overview refers to the host's description of the listing's neighbourhood, while host_about refers to the host's self-written biography. Because both texts are written by the host, I will assume that these descriptions are generally intended to emanate a positive sentiment. Another more informative method to investigate the text might be to extract bag-of-words features to identify popular words used in descriptions.

# Final preprocessor object

preprocessor = make_column_transformer(
    (KBinsDiscretizer(n_bins=20, encode="onehot"), discretization_feats),
    (make_pipeline(
        (SimpleImputer(strategy='constant', fill_value=-1)),
        StandardScaler()), numeric_feats),
    (OneHotEncoder(drop="if_binary", dtype=int, sparse_output=False), binary_feats),
    (make_pipeline(
        SimpleImputer(strategy='constant', fill_value='unknown'),
        OrdinalEncoder(categories=[ordinal_cats])), ordinal_feats),
    (make_pipeline(
        SimpleImputer(strategy='constant', fill_value='f'),
        OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore", sparse_output=False)), categorical_feats),
    (make_pipeline(
        SimpleImputer(strategy="constant", fill_value="missing"), 
        FunctionTransformer(reshape_for_countvectorizer, validate=False),
        CountVectorizer(max_features=50, stop_words="english")), nbrd_text_feat),
    (make_pipeline(
        SimpleImputer(strategy="constant", fill_value="missing"), 
        FunctionTransformer(reshape_for_countvectorizer, validate=False),
        CountVectorizer(max_features=50, stop_words="english")), host_text_feat),
    ("drop", drop_feats)
)

7. Linear models ¶

The scoring metric I've chosen to use is root mean squared error (RMSE). A lower RMSE typically means the model is performing better (however, when scores are returned with negative signs such as below, we are looking for higher RMSE values, closer to zero). With the default linear regression model using Ridge, it seems that the training set is performing a bit better than the validation set, indicating overfitting.

8. Different models ¶

In order to increase chances of finding the best results, I tested three non-linear models as well. The Ridge model ended up producing the best cv scores (though Random Forest is quite comparable), while the decision tree model ended up having the best train scores. The kNN model showed the least amount of overfitting, fastest fit time, and slowest score time, which makes sense since most of the training for kNNs occurs in the predict stage. Random forest took the longest time to fit, but had a relatively good score time compared to the other models.

In [29]:
def mean_std_cross_val_scores(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs):
    """
    Returns a pandas Series containing formatted strings of mean and std of cross validation scores.
    
    Args:
    - model: The machine learning model that will be cross-validated
    - X_train: Training data features
    - y_train: Training data target
    - kwargs: Additional keyword arguments to pass to cross_validate (e.g., scoring, cv)

    Returns:
    - A pandas Series with each cross validation scoring metric as an index and formatted strings as values
    """
    scores_df = pd.DataFrame(cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs))
    
    # Calculate mean and std of scores, rounding to 4 decimal places
    mean_scores = scores_df.mean().round(4)
    std_scores = scores_df.std().round(4)
    
    # Format results and create output Series
    formatted_scores = (mean_scores.astype(str) + " (+/- " + std_scores.astype(str) + ")")
    return pd.Series(data=formatted_scores.values, index=mean_scores.index)

10. Hyperparameter optimization ¶

In an attempt to improve my results further, I experimented with hyperparameter tuning on the non-linear models from earlier. Even though Ridge initially had the best RMSE, I chose not to continue with it knowing that a non-linear model would better be able to capture patterns between more complex relationships in the data. From the remaining estimators, RandomForestRegressor performed the best. Both with and without tuning, RF obtained a significantly better RMSE than the others.

Understandably, the features that drive the prediction of reviews_per_month the most are the subcategory reviews for each listing. Based on the model, review_scores_accuracy has the most significant effect of any feature, indicating that guests value when their stay experience lives up to their initial expectations. Intuitively, this would likely correspond with the listing's description and photos being up to date and the host communicating well about any rules, questions, or other concerns.

If a listing was new and had no reviews yet, the next most significant features seem to relate to availability of an accommodation; this includes how many bookable days the listing has open within the next year and the average minimum nights that the guest would be required to book for.

12. Results on the test set ¶

By default, sci-kit's score function for Regression problems calculates $R^2$. Since I have been using RMSE as my main metric, I defined a custom scorer to help us put the final results in perspective with the other models from before.

In [58]:
def rmse_scorer(y_preds, y_actual):
    """
    A custom scorer that calculates the RMSE scores from a model's predictions for test examples
    and the actual targets
    """
    rmse = mean_squared_error(y_actual, y_preds, squared=False)
    return -rmse

The train set achieved an RMSE score of -0.08685731189523654 and an $R^2$ score of 0.9493639749806082, and the validation set achieved an RMSE score of -0.12640112734684 and an $R^2$ score of 0.8376261365514781. While the model's performance dropped under both metrics on the test set, it seems to have performed more consistently in terms of RMSE scores. The larger gap in the $R^2$ scores suggests there is more potential to be done to lower the amount of overfitting that is occurring.

13. Summary of results ¶

Project Goal and Model

The goal of this project was to predict an Airbnb listing's review_scores_rating, as a proxy for the popularity of the listing. By creating an effective model, we could help hosts improve their listings as well as generate better algorithm recommendations for users. After testing multiple models with an assortment of parameters, we found that a random forest regressor with 22 estimators and a depth of 9 levels returned the best scores. I used RMSE as my metric of choice for this regression problem. The best model had an RMSE score of 0.12640112734684 on the test data, indicating that the standard deviation of the prediction errors (residuals) is approximately 0.1264; i.e. on average, the model's prediction of review_scores_rating would be off by ~0.1264. Not too bad!

Important Features

Looking closer into the model's findings, we (unsurprisingly) found that individual ratings on Airbnb's predetermined subcategory factors (Cleanliness, Accuracy, Check-in, Communication, Location, and Value) were the most important in influencing predictions. According to the model, the feature days_to_first_review that I engineered was the next top ranked feature importance. This suggests that Airbnb should push out recommendations for new listings with high potential for popularity (to encourage bookings and subsequently the opportunity for reviews), or even provide an incentive for users to write reviews for new listings. Finally, it seems that accessibility plays a key role in popularity; the amount of average minimum nights that guests are required to book and general availability also had a positive impact on review_scores_rating.

Although with marginal scores, many specific hosts made it on the list of top 50 feature importances too. By conducting a deeper dive into the top hosts' listings, perhaps certain patterns or consistencies can be deduced (such as description word choices or level of detail). These can then be used to help other hosts tailor their listings for increased chances of visibility.

Suggestions for Further Exploration¶

Analyzing Raw Text Features

In the EDA section, I generated a word cloud to visualize the top recurring words in listing descriptions. In my pipeline, I ended up extracting bag-of-words features. Given the sheer magnitude of features in the preprocessed dataset, I suspected that individual words might not provide as significant of a contribution to the model's predictions compared to the actual attributes of a listing. This seemed to prove correct, as only a few word features showed up near the end of the list of top 50 feature importances. I also noticed a lack of overlap from the words that were highlighted by the model and the most prominent ones in the word cloud, reminding us that the use of common terms doesn't make a description particularly better.

Given that descriptions are still a huge part of what people use to gauge whether an accommodation has the right requirements for their needs, I still think it will be a worthwhile feature to explore more in-depth. Exploring listing descriptions in tandem with search engine optimization (SEO) opportunities could unveil valuable insights into consumer preferences. By aligning key words from both consumer queries and listing descriptions, we could find hidden patterns that can be used to improve the user experience from the host-side.

Delving Deeper in Reviews

Although the specific reviews that each listing received were not available in this dataset, it may be interesting to obtain and explore the content of reviews in a future project. Those results could be used to support the findings of this project by showing hosts what causes users to leave good reviews vs bad ones. While hosts will get their own individual feedback when guests they've housed leave reviews, this sort of project could help hosts learn what they can do proactively to increase their chances of receiving positive and high reviews.
